y(d,"func:mlGridSearchCv");
s("name","mlGridSearchCv");
s(o,"Configure a cross-validation grid-search. A grid search performs\nan exhaustive search over all specified parameter values for a given\nalgorithm/estimator function. The parameters of the estimator are\noptimized by a cross-validated grid-search using the supplied\nparameter grid.\n\nThe configured grid-search can then be trained using `mlTrain`. The\nresult will be a \"trained model\" where the parameter set that produced\nthe best \"score\" will be used to make predictions using `mlPredict`.\n\n - estimator: (Str or Func) The estimator to use. Can either pass the\n name of a function in this ext, or the func itself (e.g. \"mlSvr\").\n - paramGrid: (Dict or Dict[]) The parameters to explore. The keys of\n each Dict are the parameter names for the estimator func. The value of\n each key is a list of values to explore for that parameter. Every\n combination of parameters will be tried when training the grid search.\n You may omit optional parameters for the estimator. If the last\n parameter of the estimator is a Dict, you may include the keys of that\n Dict parameter in the paramGrid (see example below).\n - opts: Options to configure the behavior of the grid search. The following\n options are supported:\n   - fold: (Number) The number of folds to apply during cross-validation.\n     (default: 3).\n   - scorer: (Str) The validation measure to use when determining the\n     best model. The following are always computed, and you may pick\n     one to use to determine the best fit (NOTE: currently the grid\n     search will pick the parameter set with the *highest* score. So it\n     is only makes sense to pick a measure where a high score means \"good\")\n     - \"r2\": The r-squared value\n     - \"explainedVariance\": Explained variance regression score\n     - \"mae\": Mean Absolute Error\n     - \"rmse\": Root Mean Squared Error\n\nThe result of running cross-validation on a parameter set is called a \"run\".\nThe results of each run can be retrieved by using `mlStats` on the\ntrained model. The stats Dict will contain a key 'runs' which is a list of\nof run results, sorted from best to worst based on the configured scorer.\n\nEach run result is itself a Dict with the following keys:\n  - \"scores\": A Dict containing all validation scores computed for that run.\n  - \"params\": A Dict containing the parameter used to configure the estimator\n    for that run.\n\nExamples:\n---------\npre>\n  // Build parameter grid to explore\n  rbfKernels: mlParamSweep(mlRbfKernel, {\"gamma\":[null, 0.2]})\n  paramGrid: [\n    {\"kernel\":rbfKernels},\n    {\"kernel\":mlLinearKernel(), \"c\":[1,10,100]},\n  ]\n\n  // Configure cross-validated grid-search\n  search: mlGridSearchCv(mlSvr, paramGrid, {\"folds\":10, \"scorer\":\"r2\"})\n\n  // The search is configured to train data on each of the following\n  // mlSvr configurations:\n  // 1) mlSvr(mlRbfKernel())\n  // 2) mlSvr(mlRbfKernel(0.2))\n  // 3) mlSvr(mlLinearKernel(), {\"c\":1})\n  // 4) mlSvr(mlLinearKernel(), {\"c\":10})\n  // 5) mlSvr(mlLinearKernel(), {\"c\":100})\n\n  // Train the grid search\n  model: mlTrain(search, x, y)\n\n  // Predict against the best model\n  predictions: mlPredict(model, predX)\n\n  // Dump the run stats for the grid search\n  stats: mlStats(model)\n  echo(stats[\"runs\"])\n<pre\n");
