y(d,"func:hisPeriodMatrix");
s("name","hisPeriodMatrix");
s(o,"Get a grid which defines the \"matrix\" of unique combinations of all the\nperiods merged together. The 'periods' parameter may be:\n  - Grid: a single grid where the first column is a \"ts\" column,\n  and all remaining columns are named anything and contain period values.\n  - Grid?[]: a list of grids where each grid has the format described above,\n\nAll input grids must be [normalized]`hisPeriodNormalize()`\n\nThe result is returned as a grid with these columns:\n  - 'ts': starting timestamp of each unique period\n  - 'dur': duration in hours of each unique period\n  - 'numTrue': number of input periods \"on\" during period\n  - 'v{i}': true of false indicating if input was \"on\" during that period\n\nExample, lets assume we have three unit runtime periods a, b, and c:\n  // look for periods where all units are all off\n  hisPeriodMatrix([a, b, c]).findAll r => r->numTrue == 0\n\n  // look for periods where all units are all on\n  hisPeriodMatrix([a, b, c]).findAll r => r->numTrue == 3\n\n  // look for periods where a and b are on, but c is off\n  hisPeriodMatrix([a, b, c]).findAll r => r->v0 and r->v1 and not r->v2\n");
